blog with Python, Nikola and Git.    &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="/posts/blogging-with-nikola-ipython-github.html"&gt;Read more...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>blogging</category><category>code</category><category>ipython</category><category>Nikola</category><category>Git</category><category>GitHub</category><guid>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/blogging-with-nikola-ipython-github.html</guid><pubDate>Sun, 18 Aug 2013 01:29:57 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Second Pelican attempt: creating a blog on GitHub with Pelican</title><link>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/second-pelican-attempt-creating-a-blog-on-github-with-pelican.html</link><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;h2&gt;How to create a blog with GitHub and Pelican (Python)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Suppose that you are curios about GitHub pages... but I don't understand their guide.&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;And suppose that you don't like Ruby but prefer Python...&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;First of all create a repo named &lt;code&gt;youname.github.com&lt;/code&gt; on your GitHub account 
(ok, maybe, before this, you have to create a GitHub account!).  &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="/posts/second-pelican-attempt-creating-a-blog-on-github-with-pelican.html"&gt;Read more...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>blogging</category><category>Python</category><category>Pelikan</category><guid>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/second-pelican-attempt-creating-a-blog-on-github-with-pelican.html</guid><pubDate>Fri, 08 Mar 2013 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Easy and fast dust removal in Digikam+Gimp</title><link>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/easy-and-fast-dust-removal-in-digikamgimp.html</link><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;It's a long time I was searching for an easy and fast way to remove dust spot from my photos.  &lt;br&gt;
Unfortunately it seem that until now no tools like "dust removal mask" or something similar are present in the open-source/linux panorama.  &lt;br&gt;
But yesterday I've found a &lt;a href="http://dodonov.net/blog/2009/12/29/cleaning-dust-on-photos-or-in-gimp-we-trust/" target="_blank"&gt;post&lt;/a&gt; explaining how to use a Gimp plugin to easy clean photos from dust spot.  &lt;br&gt;
It was not exactly what I was searching for but it worked really well.  &lt;br&gt;
The only thing to to it was to find a way to automatize the task.    &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="/posts/easy-and-fast-dust-removal-in-digikamgimp.html"&gt;Read more...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>digikam</category><category>dust</category><category>gimp</category><category>mask</category><category>photography</category><category>removal</category><category>spot</category><category>imported</category><guid>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/easy-and-fast-dust-removal-in-digikamgimp.html</guid><pubDate>Tue, 04 Sep 2012 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Imagemagick + pcal = calendar</title><link>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/imagemagick-pcal-calendar.html</link><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is the first version of the script I've created to make a calendar with photos using pcal and Imagemagik. It needs some folder and a "ps-type" font (here ChickenScratchAOE), but I think it's quite easy to understand. I have created some of the files, such as "copertina", before, using Gimp.    &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="/posts/imagemagick-pcal-calendar.html"&gt;Read more...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>calendar</category><category>code</category><category>linux</category><category>pcal</category><category>scout</category><category>imported</category><guid>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/imagemagick-pcal-calendar.html</guid><pubDate>Sat, 18 Aug 2012 22:34:15 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Latex together with matplotlib!</title><link>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/latex-together-with-matplotlib.html</link><description>&lt;p&gt;Sometimes you need to label your plot with math expression or Greek letters and ASCII is not enough.  &lt;br&gt;
Everything you need is to add to your script    &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;from&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="nn"&gt;matplotlib&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kn"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;rc&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="n"&gt;rc&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s"&gt;'font'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;**&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s"&gt;'family'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s"&gt;'sans-serif'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s"&gt;'sans-serif'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;:[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s"&gt;'Helvetica'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;]})&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="c"&gt;## for Palatino and other serif fonts use:&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="c"&gt;#rc('font',**{'family':'serif','serif':['Palatino']))&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="n"&gt;rc&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s"&gt;'text'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;usetex&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="bp"&gt;True&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p&gt;and write you text label like    &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code"&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;label&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="s"&gt;r'theoretical $f(nu)$'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>latex</category><category>matplotlib</category><category>Python</category><category>plot</category><category>imported</category><guid>brunettoziosi.eu/posts/latex-together-with-matplotlib.html</guid><pubDate>Fri, 01 Jun 2012 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item></channel></rss>